ews of the same artist over time. Others explore cases of later artists manipulating the names of earlier ones for professional or cultural gain, while still other essays reconstruct some of the forces brought to bear on artistic reception by the makers' contemporaries. The activities of artists whose stories are told here required the collaboration of numerous skilled colleagues, often deployed in the hierarchical structure of the hereditary workshop; they had to fight hard to gain social and economic recognition. The book also addresses issues of canon formation: by what complex process are some artists and objects singled out to communicate rhetorical or aesthetic meaning while others lapse into the background? Contributors include Karen L. Brock, Louise Allison Cort, Julie Nelson Davis, Christine M. E. Guth, Donald F. McCallum, Jonathan M. Reynolds, and Melinda Takeuchi.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh1 aBrock, Karen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCort, Louise Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Julie Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuth, Christine M. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCallum, Donald F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, Jonathan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakeuchi, Melinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakeuchi, Melinda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361982140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619821/original  aGBV-deGr